data.source:
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), specifically:
national affluence: OECD’s Annual National Accounts, volume 1: Comparative Tables;
import/export data: International Trade by Commodities Database;
unemployment: Labour Force Statistics—Summary Tables;

data.notes:
countries used in this study are Australia, Austria, Belgium, Canada, Denmark, Finland, France, Germany, Ireland, Italy, Japan, the Netherlands, New Zealand, Norway, Sweden, Switzerland, the United Kingdom, and the United States;
The study defines the South as Africa, Asia, Central and South America, and Oceania; the study defines the North as Europe and North America. Adjustments were made by moving Mexico and Turkey (from North America and Europe, respectively) to the South, and by moving Australia and New Zealand (from Oceania) and Israel, Japan, and South Korea (from Asia) to the North. To facilitate international comparison, values for imports and exports are expressed as a percentage of GDP for all countries. 
national affluence is measured as a country’s gross domestic product (GDP) divided by its total population, with GDP expressed in U.S. dollars at prices and purchasing parities (PPP) from the year 2000.
